Project: No-show Appointments Dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

  • ‘ScheduledDay’ tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • ‘Neighborhood’ indicates the location of the hospital.
  • ‘Scholarship’ indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família.
  • Be careful about the encoding of the last column: it says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up.

Goal

  • What factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

Data Cleaning¶

Here I will clean the dataset and try to make columns more understandable for reader

  • Removing 'Age' outliers
  • Recorrect Columns Names (Hipertension, Handcap, Scholarship, Diabetes, Neighborhood, No-show) to (Has Hypertension, Handicap Level, Family Allowance, Has Diabetes, Hospital Location, Attendance)
  • Convert columns (ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay) into datetime.
  • Drop Columns (PatientId, AppointmentID)
  • Rename Genders

Removing 'Age' Outliers¶

Age can not be -1

In [12]:
df.drop(df.index[df['Age'] < 0], inplace=True)

What is the relation between Attendance and Patients who recieved an SMS for the appointment?¶

In [31]:
SMS_Attended = df[df['Attendance']=='Attended'].groupby('Attendance')['SMS_received'].value_counts()
SMS_Attended.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(15,5));
SMS_Missed = df[df['Attendance']=='Missed Appointment'].groupby('Attendance')['SMS_received'].value_counts()
SMS_Missed.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(15,5), bottom=SMS_Attended, color='orange');

x_ticks = ['Did not Receive SMS', 'Received SMS']
plt.ylabel('Count of Patients', fontsize=font_size1);
plt.title('Attendance Relationship to receiving SMS before the Appointment', fontsize=font_size1);
plt.xticks(fontsize= font_size2+2, rotation='horizontal', ticks=[0,1], labels=x_ticks);
plt.yticks(fontsize= font_size2)
plt.legend(['Attended', 'Missed Appointment']);
In [32]:
df.groupby('Attendance')['SMS_received'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', figsize=(15,5));

x_ticks = ['Attended, No SMS', 'Attended, Received SMS', 'Did not Attend, No SMS', 'Did not Attend, Received SMS']
plt.ylabel('Count of Patients', fontsize=font_size1);
plt.title('Attendance Relationship to receiving SMS before the Appointment', fontsize=font_size1);
plt.xticks(fontsize= font_size2+2, rotation='horizontal', ticks=[0,1,2,3], labels=x_ticks);
plt.yticks(fontsize= font_size2);

for num, value in enumerate(df.groupby('Attendance')['SMS_received'].value_counts()):
        plt.text(num-0.06, value+500, str(value), fontweight='bold');

Here we will find that patients who have recieved an SMS for the appointment have more chance to attend, as patients who recieved SMS and missed the appointment are only 27.6% of total patients who recieved SMS.

Conclusions¶

  • We found that patients who have recieved an SMS for the appointment have more chance to attend, as patients who recieved SMS and missed the appointment are only 27.6% of total patients who recieved SMS.
  • We found that patients who have recieved an SMS for the appointment have more chance to attend, as patients who recieved SMS and missed the appointment are only 27.6% of total patients who recieved SMS.
  • We found that patients who have Diabetes have a small chance to miss his appointment, as the percentage of patients who missed their appointment with Diabetes is less than those healthy ones by 1%.
  • We found that patients who have hypertension have a small chance to miss his appointment, as the percentage of patients who miss their appointment with hypertension is less than those healthy ones by 3.5%.
  • We found that patients who have family allowance have a higher chance to miss their appointment, as the percentage of patients who missed their appointment is more than those who attended by 2.2%.
  • We found that work days had attendance more than weekends, and hospitals has no appointments at Sundays. The highest day of appointments is Wednesday by 25867 appointments followed by Tuesday by 25640 appointments, and the least one is Saturday with total 39 appointments.
  • We found that less males have family allowance than females, as 11.8% of females have family allowance but only 5% of males have it. Also found when comparing attendance and its relation to family allowance we will find that more patients who have family allowance tend to miss their appointment more than patients without it, as 5% of males attended at time but 6.1% missed the appointment, and for females 11.8% attended but 14.4% missed the appointment.
